Do both classes have to be EE/CS for us to use this form?
No, it is only prompted to appear by your trying to enroll in conflicting courses. Nice idea though! :)
What do you do if one of the conflicting classes is an upper div CS class that you can't add? In that case, I won't be prompted the SIS form altogether, right?
What do you mean by a course that you can't add? In that you don't meet the enrollment restrictions, or you would exceed the units / et cetera? If so, this form doesn't let you bypass those.
No, I'm referring to the problem where there is no discussion to choose

Not sure I understand everything, but here's my attempt to answer:

If you can't add the course, you will presumably add the course at a future date. At that time, the form should appear.
I think anon was talking about the issue described in @3842, which has been resolved.
Is it possible to submit the SIS form before your Phase I? I ask so that I can enroll in conflicting classes as soon as my Phase I starts
Also, how do we know if/when our request has been "processed" ? Do we get another notification on our dashboard?
Hopefully one of your classmates can answer this. As I said here, we receive no training on this and can't even see the form as we're not students.

Or try asking SIS

SIS users can contact SIS Production Support in three ways:

  1. E-mail:  sishelp@berkeley.edu
  2. Call: 510-664-9000 (then select 6 from the menu)
  3. Submit a ticket: https://berkeley.service-now.com/ess/create_incident
    - In the “Affected Service” section, please choose “SIS - Student Information Systems”

(Note: CalNet ID required to submit a ticket)

Is there any kind of confirmation we should be able to see on our dashboard, or elsewhere, indicating that our SIS form went through/ is pending? I submitted one, but the app simply closed out when I clicked "submit". Would be nice to know that it did indeed go through so that I don't wait 3 days for nothing.

Please see the note above that says if you don't meet enrollment priorities you won't be enrolled. See enrollment priorities here: https://eecs.berkeley.edu/resources/undergrads/eecs/degree-reqs/enrollment-policy and https://eecs.berkeley.edu/resources/undergrads/cs/degree-reqs/enrollment-policy. Not being declared yet doesn't mean you shouldn't fill out the form, just that you'll want to check that the specific class has open seats for your category.
Okay got it, thanks!

How does this work if you are currently an undeclared student and not 100% sure you will be accepted into the courses? 

Can I still fill out this form?

No. The SIS form will not be generated until you try to enroll in the course. 

The google form links should only be filled out as per the clearly stated instructions "If you have filled out the SIS form, but your request has still not been processed after 36 hour..."
To clarify: if we want to Phase II a CS class, can we fill out the form now since it'll be processed starting in Phase II?
You will need to wait for there to be open spots in 194-26 before you can utilize the conflict form.

What do you mean?  There are 98/141 spots enrolled right now for 194-26 according to Campus Solutions.  If I recall correctly, you cannot get off the waitlist if you're enrolled in a conflicting class.  I'm wondering if I should not enroll in 176 right now to maximize the possibility of me getting into 194 or if that won't have an affect on the waitlist processing at all.

Yes, you are correct in that you can't get off the waitlist if you are in a conflicting class.

Thus, you will need to utilize this form. When you fill this form out during Phase II (or afterwards), at that point, if there are no open seats in 194-26, then the advisors won't be able to let you into the class.
Okay, thanks!

If I am enrolled in a class that conflicts with a class I'm waitlisted in, will that affect my ability to get off the waitlist if I fill out the conflict form?  I am waitlisted for 194-26 and enrolled in 176 but would only take one out of those two classes since they're at the same time and my first choice is 194 which I'm waitlisted for.  I just want to make sure I can prioritize getting off the waitlist even though there are conflicts.
You will be allowed onto the waitlist. You will not be able to get off of the waitlist, without using this form.

If I am enrolled an a L&S breadth class that has a lecture from 2-5, but I want to get on the wait-list of CS170 in Phase 2, will this enrollment conflict form allow me to enroll in CS170 if I get off of the waitlist, even though there is a lecture conflict? Or, when I sign up for the wait-list in Phase 2, will it tell prevent me from the waitlist?

I know that I will be able to fill out the SIS conflict form once I try to enroll in 16A. However, I was waitlisted for 16A (even though there seem to be many seats left), which means that I can't fill out the form. What should I do? You could add the second course and fill out the SIS form that is generated.

Is there a overriding conflict form for SU 17?

@3869

CS 61B Lecture Conflict

I have discussion for an R1B requirement during CS 61B lecture next fall. I've heard that I can still be enrolled in 61B, but I might need to fill out a form or contact someone. Does anyone know how to proceed from here? Currently I'm "enrolled" in that R1B but not in 61B on CalCentral.

Contact the instructor
Instructor wont tell me
The instructor is the only person who can decide to grant an alternate final exam. No one else can.
Even if we override, and even if there is webcast so we can do it in case of conflicting lecture, how can we find out if we can resolve final exam time conflicts?

If it's an EE/EECS course, it means I wasn't able to override it for a variety of reasons (some of which are listed above). If it's a unit problem, I typically email the student to let them know, so it was probably not for that reason. 

CS course conflicts are not being processed until Phase II.
i filled out the form 2 weeks ago and have not gotten a response. Does this mean it was not approved or just being reviewed?
I'm sorry, I don't understand your question. You report being on the waitlist and are asking if you should drop the course to re-add to the waitlist? Do you need to change something?
Resolving, as you look enrolled

I want to use this to override a 61A lecture time for an EE 16A lab. I'm currently enrolled in 16 units. However, I used the swap function on one of the four courses I'm enrolled in for 16A, so I'm technically on the waitlist for 16A (number 330). My question is, should I drop the class I want to swap and get on the waitlist for 16A again or will my current situation work?
If you're enrolled, you will see that on CalCentral. We will not contact you to let you know you're enrolled or if there are issues with your enrollment.

That's fine, as long as the course you're using to add it is CS

Assuming it's been more than a couple of days, submit the cs override form.
I submitted it a few days ago. Will it still work even though I'm #31 on the waitlist for 189, and thus not able to be enrolled until spots open up?

"If you have a time-conflict with one of the classes you are waitlisted for, how will you ever get off the waitlist?

You will never get off of the waitlist if this is the case. You can drop the class you are enrolled in, try setting up a future swap, or contact the major department. Enrollment managers do have the power to override a time-conflict if they see just reason to do so."
"Please follow up with the department regarding your waitlisted course that is generating a time conflict. Unfortunately SIS Production Support is not authorized to manage enrollment or waitlist of classes since we are a technical support team."
Who in the department would this be referring to?

That's basically just referring to this post, which is the department staff volunteering to override these time conflicts.

But they can't override a time conflict if there's not space in the class.
But there will never be space in the course, since any opened space will automatically be filled from the waitlist?
As long as there are people on the waitlist who aren't otherwise blocked from enrolling, then yes, that is correct.

You should try the form again with a different section.
Steven's advice is correct.

Hi! Has the processing for CS conflict override requests for Phase II started yet?

Essentially, I am having problems requesting an SIS override on my Calcentral. I am following the instructions here: http://sis.berkeley.edu/sites/default/files/override_process_-_enrollment_time_conflict_v2-2.pdf

And even though I have a conflict with another class, I don't have the option to request an override with SIS. I was number 22 on the waitlist for CS188 before expansion. Now I'm number 6, and my friends who were 70 were added, and I think it was because of the conflict that I wasn't. What should I do? Would the CS Conflict Override form suffice?

If you're waitlist for a class that conflicts for a class you're already enrolled in, you'll never get off the waitlist. The conflict form won't help with that. 

Your only options are to wait until you're the last and only person on the waitlist, and a spot opens up in the class, or drop the conflicting class.

Source - I was in the same situation; there's no good solution

Nitpick: you don't have to wait until you're the only person on the waitlist.

You just have to wait until everyone else on the waitlist also can't get into the class (whether due to a conflict with their schedule or otherwise), and you are the first person on the waitlist. Presumably (hopefully) not many, but still.

But yes, to elaborate: the advisors can only move you into the class if there is space in the class, so you have to wait until then before filling out the conflict form.

Thanks for the responses! However, I'm not sure I understand what's going on. So the classes in question are Ling150 and CS188. I'm currently enrolled in Ling150, and I'm number 6 in CS188.

So it sounds like if I'm number 6 on the waitlist for CS188 now, I will never get into the class because of the conflict. Is that correct? Apologies for reiterating, but I thought that it was because of the conflict that I wasn't added to CS188 in the first place. I had phase ii'd on the first day, and was number 22, and my friends with later phase dates were higher (like number 70). Because CS188 doubled in class size and therefore had 300 more seats to fill, if the waitlists were processed on a first-come-first serve basis, I should have been added to the class. But I wasn't, and I suspect it was because of the conflict. Am I misunderstanding something here?

Yes, you will never get into the class off of the waitlist because of the conflict. The waitlists are processed on a first-come-first-serve basis, but it'll skip over you since you are unable to get into the class.

The conflict wouldn't have been what had caused you to get onto the waitlist; the class would have also been full. (If the class had open seats, then you would have been offered the conflict override form when you attempted to enroll.)
Hello! For courses such as CS188 that do not have discussion or section times listed, can we just leave them blank when filling out the CS Overide Conflict form?
The override form will only be processed if there is space in the course. I don't believe there is any for 170.  @Cindy Conners
So in this case, my best bet would be to drop my conflict class and only add it back once I get into 170?

Hmm no, because you won't get into a course if you have a conflict.

I would suggest emailing cs-scheduling@berkeley.edu for advice if Cindy or Michael-David don't respond by Monday. However, please only do this if you're in the top 10-15% of the waitlist. This class isn't expected to be expanded so the waitlist will not all be accommodated.

If anon drops their conflicting class, they wouldn't have a conflict anymore, so they should be able to enroll in 170 then.

If, at that point, there's space in the conflicting class, they could then use the regular SIS conflict override form to get into that other class.

Sorry, I somehow misunderstood the most recent question. Effects of working past 11pm. 


Steven's response is true if there is space for you in both these courses. There is *1* available seat in CS 170. I heard this is due to a glitch.

There most definitely is not space in CS170. I have been processing the conflict overrides when I can but there's nothing I can do for CS170 unless they decide to open more space.

Yes, there is a system glitch that holds back a couple of seats & that I have to manually fill. I took the first 2 people from the wait list yesterday & manually moved them in so there are no more open seats in this class.

I'm 37 on the 170 waitlist which is well within 10%, so I'm hoping to get in once the semester starts. My only concern is that I will not be able to access webcasts for the class that I'm planning to temporarily drop (to resolve the conflict). Will I be able to access the webcasts for 170 if I'm waitlisted? If yes, I think dropping my conflicting class until I get into 170 (hopefully) would be best.

Not directly, no. Some course staff are willing to provide webcast links to waitlisted students (during the first few weeks); you should contact the two courses' instructors for information about this.
Ok, thank you!

Is there any way I can confirm that the Conflict Override form that I submitted for 170 via the Google Form has been accepted? I just want to make sure that the conflict won't prevent me from getting off the waitlist if/when space opens up.
You will need to fill out the conflict form again when you attempt to enroll in the second class.
So if 70 conflicts for two classes, and even though i already did a form for 70 once, I have to do another form?

The form just means someone manually put you into 70. It doesn't give you any "override" privileges in the system for any other courses (or even the same conflicting course, if you drop it and reenroll).
If I'm 6 on the waitlist though, and say six people drop, then I will get into the class? No problems?

No, you'll be blocked from enrolling, since you have a time conflict. If there's no one else on the waitlist after you, then there'll be an empty space, so you can fill out the time conflict form then.

So if the concurrent form went through (I enrolled in 70 and am on the waitlist), can I sign up for another class that conflicts with it?

I am already signed up for a class that conflicts with 70 on Wednesday, but now I want to add a class that conflicts with it on Friday as well. Is this doable, or will I be dropped from 70 if I get into the class later on?
After.

After reading your other comments I think I understand this correctly, but just to be sure:

If I'm currently on the waitlist for CS70 and fully enrolled in a conflicting class, being position number 1 on the waitlist is not sufficient; I should wait until everyone else who does not have a conflict or other restriction either leaves the waitlist or gets enrolled. At that point there will actually be space to enroll in the course, and I can fill out the conflict override form here. 

Is that all correct?
Yes.

I'm currently waitlisted for CS 70 at position #49. Another class I have enrolled in has a time-conflict with Friday's CS70 lecture. The SIS conflict form was not generated for me as CS70 was full when I tried enrolling in it and was hence placed on the waitlist.

Should I fill out the Google Time Conflict form before or after there is open space in the class?
the forms are processed every 3 days. If there's room, Cindy manually enrolls you. If not, the responses are cleared. Please complete the form every 3 days until enrolled.
When will this be processed next? Enrolled in a course and want to get in before it fills up.
Have you tried using "Options" to move onto the waitlist for the lab you want + the conflict form?

If you're enrolled and want to just switch your lab or discussion, but can't due to a time conflict, you can still use our forms. Just indicate somewhere that you're enrolled b/c we would use a different function to change your secondary section and not fully enroll you.
Okay, thank you!

How do I go about overriding a change in a lab section? All I want to do is swap from one lab section to another without re-enrolling in the course. However the form doesn't account for this since it requires me to be waitlisted in the course (which is impossible).
I don't monitor the form but that sounds appropriate to me.
yep - that's the way to do it.

Is it okay to Request Course Override for enrolling into a CS-198 Decal course when I have another course in its exact time frame? Also if yes, if the CS conflict form requests the lab and discussion times and the Decal doesn't have a lab or discussion, do I just apply "N/A" to both response?

I'm not sure if this has been asked already (I couldn't find it anywhere), but will overrides still be possible for spring 2018? I'd like to take some combination of 151, 170, and 188, and all three have the same lecture time.

history.content:
Dear Students,

We will continue to override time conflicts for students for this fall. Please see information below.

The enrollment system does not allow you to enroll directly in classes that have time conflicts. This must be processed by the SIS team (instructions). 

If you have filled out the SIS form, but your request has still not been processed after 36 hours, we will override class conflicts for you via a Google form (links below), space permitting. Please note that by filling out the form(s), you agree to have a class conflict overridden for you. It is your responsibility to check the attendance policies and make plans for conflicting exams. You must be waitlisted for the class in which you're requesting to enroll.

Please do not contact us after filling out the form to check on the status of your request. We will process the requests as soon as we are able.

CS Conflict Override Form (will be processed starting in Phase II)

EE Conflict Override Form (use this form for EECS classes as well)

**Use the CS form, if you're trying to enroll in a CS class. Use the EE form, if you're trying to enroll in an EE or EECS class.**

**Please make sure you have checked your enrolled and waitlisted units. Phase I maximum is 13.5, Phase II is 17.5, and the Adjustment Period is 20.5. We cannot override the maximum units for you and this causes a delay in processing requests.**

Note: If the class is full and/or you do not meet enrollment priorities, you will not be enrolled. If you do not provide 2nd and 3rd choices for secondary sections (if applicable) and your first choice fills, you will not be enrolled.

Sincerely,

EECS Student Affairs

FAQ:

Q: When should I use the form? 

A: After you have first filled out the SIS form and waited 36 hours. Instructions here. The notification takes about 1 hour to appear on your dashboard.

Q: Can conflicts for classes other than EE/CS/EECS be overridden?

A: Not by the EECS Department. See information on class conflicts here.

Q: How long will it take for a conflict to be overridden?

A: We will check the form every few days. CS requests will begin to be processed during Phase II.
